body:
__TLDR__: Specifying keys when mapping from data to components feels wrong to me even after several years. It would be really nice if components could specify their own `key` instead.

This is how you supply keys when rendering a list of components:

```jsx
const User = ({ name, email }) => (
  <div>{name}, {email}</div>
);

const View = ({ users }) => (
  <div>{users.map(user => <User key={user.email} {...user} />)}</div>
); 
```

This has always felt dirty to me because in order to do render a list of `User`, `View` has to know implementation details about `User`. From a separation of concerns standpoint this feels icky. Also, this creates some sort of tight coupling problem between `User` and any component that needs to render a list of it. If you have many lists of `User` in your app and need to refactor it, best case scenario is you have to do a lot of search-replace and in the worst case you get bugs.

I wish there was a way for components to handle the mapping of `props -> key` internally. Maybe something like:

```jsx
const User = ({ name, email }) => (
  <div key={email}>{name}, {email}</div>
);

const View = ({ users }) => (
  <div>{users.map(user => <User {...user} />)}</div>
); 
```

More possible solutions [below](https://github.com/facebook/react/issues/15592#issuecomment-491265016).

If enough people like this idea I hope you'd consider an official API/solution that allowed this. :) 

EDIT: Removed some arrow function related stuff because in hindsight it making my point confusing.
